The translation of the sentence "Fukushima et l’effondrement des produits dérivés" from French to English is:  "Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives"  This sentence likely refers to the impact of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster on financial derivatives markets.
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquakes, tsunami, and nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates substantial profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
However, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
For the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century tsunami, combined with typically harmless design flaws, caused the cessation of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
Regarding financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repurchase markets, has damaged the ability of important financial institutions to meet their debt obligations.
Despite the fundamental risks originating outside of the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgages for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck ensured that the systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers — all with significant investments in derivatives and/orrepos — went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand the risks and design flaws of Fukushima fairly well.
One cannot say the same for the risks of derivatives products that have shaken the global economy.
In Fukushima, the teams of workers are bravely attempting to stop the radiation leaks.
On the contrary, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivative products and similar financial structures over the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of the euro's fluctuation but does not want yen risk, while for another actor, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first one promises to provide euros by June 1st, and the second one promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
The translation of the sentence "Les repos sont des transactions financières." from French to English is:  "Repos are financial transactions."
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bonds or mortgage debts, in exchange for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase - or repurchase, as noted).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repo transactions represents a significant portion of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which means that simple financial tremors can strongly affect them.
Some institutions may then find themselves deprived of funding through repos, as happened in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Individually considered, transactions involving derivatives or pensions are not particularly culpable.
Each separately transfers risk in a legitimate manner to those who are better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are overused by institutions that are systemically vital, they can cause the financial system to collapse due to its design flaws.
Today, roughly 70% of the balance sheets of major American financial companies are still composed of very short-term loans, such as those payable the day after tomorrow.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and pensions from most usual constraints in case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivative contracts or loans with financially weakened financial institutions may seize the company's assets before—and at the expense of—its normal creditors. By doing so, they can dictate the company’s fate when, with just a bit more time, the company might have been able to survive.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because derivative and mortgage-backed securities investors find themselves at the back of the line for reimbursements in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely monitoring their counterparties' solvency and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be reimbursed anyway.
Certainly, someone must be the first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because exemptions for derivative products and repo place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, we would expect that others would have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is too often the American government, as a guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions. Yet, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
He is not financially agile; he often confines himself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank legislation.
But he did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives,repos, and credit-default swaps (credit-event derivatives, as noted) were not given preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often for their counterparts to be capitalized adequately.
They accepted the risk associated with ultra-low capitalizations, particularly when it came primarily to the money of the American government; they would be less likely to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives differently the risks of the type Fukushima and the risks associated with derivative products.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are significant, causing a slowdown in an industry that must address security concerns.
But the risks associated with derivatives and repo markets are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for policymakers.
During a crisis, these markets attract both the public's attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, allowing the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami risks through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to foresee nuclear power plants capable of maintaining cold fuel rods even in the case of a total loss of electrical power supply.
On the other hand, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damages that making derivatives a priority and relying on them in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unforeseen changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline among the major financial institutions.
It seems as though we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully shift the risk associated with their derivative product transactions and decisions to the investors themselves when they conduct transactions with financial institutions that are systemically vital.
Instead, we survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
